Allocating health care resources. The vexing case of rehabilitation.

Callahan D(1).

Author information:
(1)Hastings Center, New York, NY 10510.

Comment in
    Am J Phys Med Rehabil. 1993 Oct;72(5):331-2.

The allocation of resources to rehabilitation is beset with many difficulties. 
Among them are the general crisis in the American health care system and the 
problem of how to make a case for the role of rehabilitation. Rehabilitation 
must be prepared to show how and why it is a good medical and social investment 
in relation to other needs. Rehabilitation has played a secondary role in the 
American health care system because of overemphasis on curative and 
life-extending medicine. Rehabilitation must work to show that money invested in 
caring is as well spent as money aiming at the extension of life. It must also 
establish a fresh new vision of health care in general as well as illustrate 
where rehabilitation stands in a more integrated and coherent health care 
system. Improved quality of life, which rehabilitation can provide, is as 
important as saving and extending life.

