986. J Biosoc Sci. 1993 Apr;25(2):155-67. doi: 10.1017/s0021932000020460.

Emerging patterns of child-spacing in Canada.

Rahim A(1), Ram B.

Author information:
(1)Demography Division, Statistics Canada, Ottawa.

This study used data from the 1984 Family History Survey conducted by Statistics 
Canada to examine recent trends and patterns of child-spacing among currently 
married women. Life table and proportional hazards estimates show that Canadian 
women, particularly those in younger age groups with higher education and longer 
work experience, start having children late, but have subsequent children rather 
quickly. This suggests that such women tend to complete childbearing within a 
compressed time period.

PIP: With a low and stable family size, understanding birth spacing contributes 
to firmer projections of fertility and the socioeconomic status of women. In 
this study, the aim was to examine the socioeconomic differences in the spacing 
of first, second, third, and fourth births in Canada from data in the 1984 
Family History Survey. The subsample included 2534 women aged 18-44 years who 
were currently living with their first husband. Confounding effects were 
eliminated by excluding women with a disrupted marital history and premarital 
fertility (births 7 months prior to first marriage). Also excluded were higher 
than 4th order births. Life table techniques are used to counteract the 
censoring found in cross-sectional data collected at one point in time, which 
does not provide complete reproductive histories. Analysis was conducted for 
women aged 18-34 years and 35-44 years in order to validate reproductive history 
life events. Analysis of unweighted data involved proportional hazards models. 
The results show that having a first birth within 8 months of first marriage 
occurred in or was likely to occur in nearly 14% of currently married women 
18-44 years. Within 24 months of marriage, 52% of women aged 35-44 and 44% of 
women aged 18-34 years were likely to have their first child. Within 6 years of 
marriage, 85% of women were likely to have their first child. Canadian women, 
particularly younger women, delay childbearing; subsequent children are also 
delayed. The effect of marriage age on birth interval is minimal for second and 
third birth intervals. Age at first birth was the most influential factor 
affecting birth interval; there was an association between young age and shorter 
second birth interval. Second birth intervals for women aged 35-44 years, who 
gave birth to their first child before the age of 23 years, was 18.7 months; 
interval increased as the age of first birth increased. For third births, the 
median duration declined as the age of the mother at first birth increased. The 
results of the multivariate analysis showed that length of first birth interval 
had a negative impact on length of second birth interval. There was a strong and 
significant positive relationship between age at first birth and second birth 
interval. A shorter second birth interval was found for women who were less 
educated and more educated than women with 8-13 years of schooling. There was 
also a curvilinear relationship between duration of first work interruption and 
child spacing.

