The effectiveness of ovarian cancer screening. A decision analysis model.

Schapira MM(1), Matchar DB, Young MJ.

Author information:
(1)Medical College of Wisconsin, Milwaukee.

Comment in
    Ann Intern Med. 1993 Dec 1;119(11):1151; author reply 1152.
    Ann Intern Med. 1993 Dec 1;119(11):1151; author reply 1152.
    Ann Intern Med. 1993 Dec 1;119(11):1151-2.
    Ann Intern Med. 1993 Jun 1;118(11):901-2.

OBJECTIVE: To estimate the effectiveness of ovarian cancer screening with CA 125 
and transvaginal sonography.
DESIGN: Decision analysis was used to examine the no-screen compared with the 
screen strategy.
SETTING: Estimates of cancer incidence, survival, and life expectancy were 
derived from population-based data and clinical series.
SUBJECTS: A cohort of 40-year-old women of all races and residing in the United 
States.
INTERVENTIONS: A one-time screening intervention. The criterion standard for 
diagnosis of ovarian cancer was evaluation with exploratory laparotomy.
MAIN OUTCOME MEASURE: Average years of life expectancy gained by women in the 
screened group.
RESULTS: Screening for ovarian cancer with a combination of CA 125 and 
transvaginal sonography increases the average life expectancy in the population 
by less than 1 day.
CONCLUSIONS: Given the limited effect on overall life expectancy, it is unlikely 
that mass screening for ovarian cancer with CA 125 and transvaginal sonography 
would be an effective health policy.

